I suspect a similar thing is happening with Martin if his intent truly was to have ambiguously moral characters.

@gerudoking3180 It´s not that complicated or deep. Martin is a modern writer, who just wanted to go against the common tropes of fantasy or entertainment literature, where most of the time the hero wins, and the hero is not following some super moralistic, abstract code, but is simply a likable character, who does the "right thing", the right thing being standing against obnoxious villains. There is no deeper meaning behind that, and Martin goes against it, for obvious, narrative, suspense-related reasons. Martin does not give a fuck about catholic christianity, because it just does not play a big role in entertainment anyhow and is not important for his private life, he is a lefty, after all. Remember, most of the heroes we love and like are NOT christian heroes at all. They are actually "heathen" heroes with a modern twist. 

There are obvious protagonists and heroes in GOT, like John Snow or Tyrion Lannister or Bran or Arya. And there are obvious villains like the Boltons, like the Cersei. We also have a great nihilistic antagonist in the OTHERS and a hero, that is supposed to defeat them in Dany and her dragons.

GOT is best understood as modern "grim dark" fantasy, that goes against fantasy tropes to maximize suspense and entertainment. The problem with it is that certain decisions of that direction CAN ruin entertainment and suspense, if one is not too careful. For example, Martin is very bad in giving his heroes the abilities to actually stand against the villains. We see that with Jon Snow or Bran. I mean, even Dany is not exactly well equipped to deal with the Others. On the other side, the villains are very overpowered, very clever, very dangerous. A fascinating example is Jaime Lannister, who was extremely dangerous as a villain, and became an impotent slob when his right hand was cut off and he became a hero. So there is a big assymetry between the heroes and the villains, that can instill the feeling, that it is a non moralistic play, a cynical dance on certain postmodernist ideas. But it isn´t really. It is not that deep. Instead it is more the consequence of grim dark fantasy with additional decisions, that came home too roost.

